Abstract: Accurate forecasts of macroeconomic variables are crucial inputs into the decisions of economic
agents and policy makers. Exploiting inherent aggregation structures of such variables, we
apply forecast reconciliation methods to generate forecasts that are coherent with the aggregation constraints. 
We generate both point and probabilistic forecasts for the first time in the
macroeconomic setting. Using Australian GDP we show that forecast reconciliation not only
returns coherent forecasts but also improves the overall forecast accuracy in both point and
probabilistic frameworks.
